145= change, and it's March 2002.  So this shows you
146= became production manager, finishing, March 2002.
147=     Q  Yes.
148=     A  How long were you in management 
149=  before manager of finishing?
150=     A  Well let me see I became a manager in 
151=  JUly of 2000, so a little under two years.
fmt=pb
152=     Q   Did the Metro Waste Commission inspect 
153= the DC Corp facility in Wilmington California
154= since you have been at the Wilmington
155= location?
156=     A   Twice.
157=     Q   And when were the inspections
158= conducted by the Metro Waste Commission of
159= the Wilmington facility during the time
160= you have been employed at the Wilmington
161= location?
162=     A   The first one was some time during the
163= middle of May 2001, and I believe they started
164= again either in December of 2003 or January
165= 2005.  With their schedule in all this time,
166= they stretched it all of over three and a half
167= weeks.  It went over a couple months as far as
168= the calendar goes.
169=     Q   Has the Wilmington facility of
170= DC Corp ever received any sort of citation
171= from the Metro Waste Commission while you have
172= been at that location?
173=     A   Yes.
174=     Q   What citations has the Wilmington
175= facility of DC Corp received from the Metro
176= Waste Commission while you've been employed
fmt=pb
177= at the Wilmington location?
178=     A   One I remember was a citation for
179= a recalled shipment of bottled water.  That
180= citation was caused by a mistake in the 
181= shipping dock.  We had inadvertantly shipped
182= out unreleased product that was under
183= quarantine pending sterility testing.  And then
184= the Metro Waste Commission ruled that because we
185= manufactured the water, that we were
186= responsible for that.
187=         However, second MWC auditor, who
188= had actually did our audit, disagreed with the
189= initial finding, and still being contested right
190= now.  But as it stands right now, it's counted
191= against us.
192=          Other than that, they have very
193= minor procedural issues, typos, clarifications.
194= DC Corp's always had an outstanding relationship
195= with the MWC.  We are always in compliance.
196=     Q   When was the citation in connection
197= with the recalled water that was produced at
198= the Wilmington facility?
199=     A   That was the one in December of 2003.
200= That's what triggered our the initial audit, even
201= though we were due for a routine inspection in a
fmt=pb
202= couple months.
203=     Q   Other than the citation for the recall
204= of the water produced at the Wilmington
205= California DC Corp facility that you have just
206= mentioned in December of 2003, what other
207= deficiencies were noted by the MWC in its
208= inspection or audit of the Wilmington
209= facility?
210=          MR. MCAVOY: Objection; asked and
211= answered.
212=          THE WITNESS: Pardon me?
213=          MR. MCAVOY: I'm objecting.  You just
214= answered.  You can answer it again.
215=          THE WITNESS: They cited us for minor
216= violations of procedures that weren't clear.
217= They recommended that in our fill station
218= enclosures that we sample the fill station
219= enclosures every shift instead of once a day.
220=         One of the things they wanted to
221= see is when we find something that's out of
222= tolerance in the lab or somewhere, they wanted
223= more of an investigation done.  So they wanted
224= the procedure to call out the actual -  you know
225= conduct an investigation every time there was
226= any sort of process intolerance.
fmt=pb
227=         And then they wanted us to do what
228= they call our media fills.  They wanted us to
229= do what we call interventions.   Interventions
230= are what you do when you have to stop the
231= machine or access it or do anything that's
232= considered normal production routes.
233=         They wanted to see us plan them.
234= Even though we did them, we didn't have a plan
235= schedule.  So, again, a very minor note.  Those
236= have already all been corrected and submitted
237= back to the MWC.
238= BY MS. WEGNER:
239=     Q   What is a media fill?
240=     A   Media fill is what the MWC considers
241= machine validation.  You're required to do it
242= at a minimum of every six months; twice a year.
243= What that does is that puts super food into the
244= fill system to show that your machine is
245= capable of making sterile bottles.
246=         If there is any bacteria, mold,
247= spores, anything at all in your fill system,
248= the media will be that stuff and make it grow
249= super fast.  
250=     Q   How does the media fill interact with
251= mold?
fmt=pb
252=     A   I don't understand the question.  Can
253= you repeat it.
254=          MS. COWENS: Read it back, would you,
255= Rhonda?
256=                      (Whereupon the record was
257=                       read as requested.)
258=          MR. MCAVOY: Do you understand that any
259= better?
260=          THE WITNESS: Not really, no.  We
261= didn't do clinical studies or anything like
262= that.  I mean, we did research on mold, but we
263= didn't ...
264= BY MS. COWENS:
265=     Q   Isn't it true that Mr. Walter Evans
266= recommended that a professional mold abatement
267= service be contracted to clean up the Wilmington
268= California location of DC Corp sometime in
269= 2005?
270=     A   He recommended that his group do the
271= cleanup.  And the cleaning of the second floor
272= and warehouse, we used an independent construction
273= company, so that was contracted out.  We did
274= everything that Evans recommended.  We just
275= did not use him for the abatement process.  His
276= price for all of the cleaning we did was just
fmt=pb
277= too high.
278=     Q   And you indicated that you did hire
279= outside services to perform some of the mold
280= cleanup -
281=     A   Yes.
282=     Q   - at the plant?
283=     A   Yes.
284=     Q   And who did you hire?
285=     A   To change the insulation in other
286= areas where we discovered - other areas that
287= needed to be worked on was a company called
288= ABC, Alpha Building Contractors, something or
289= another.  Same contractors that are building
290= our clean room.  The name of the company - we
291= actually rented a warehouse, we then emptied
292= the entire warehouse, we hired a company called
293= Jam Pro to come in and power wash the
294= warehouse.  The whole building was cleaned from
295= top to bottom, three different groups.
296=     Q   And the third group involved in
297= cleaning was -
298=     A   Internal -
299=     Q   Internal?
300=     A   Yeah, like it says on this memo right
301= over here.
